<DocsLayout title="Evaluation & Trust" section="Concepts"><Hero eyebrow="Concept 06" title="If it cannot be measured, it cannot be trusted." lede="A convincing demo is not evidence. Enterprise trust comes from repeatable evaluation and observable behavior." reading="10 min" difficulty="Core" prerequisite="Explicit State" />
<Question>What evidence proves that a prompt, model, or tool change made the system better?</Question>
<Diagram title="Trust is built from repeatable evidence" chart={chart} />
<Principle title="Measure components and outcomes."><p>Evaluate extraction, retrieval, tool selection, final task success, latency, cost, and safety separately before combining them into one release decision.</p></Principle>
<CaseBlock title="A bid agent is judged by business errors."><p>The important metrics are missed high-value notices, false pushes, field accuracy, approval adoption, latency, and cost—not how fluent the explanation sounds.</p></CaseBlock>
<Decision question="Why not rely only on an LLM judge?" answer="A model judge is useful for semantic quality but must be calibrated against deterministic rules and human-reviewed examples." alternative="No single aggregate score that hides failure modes." />
<Takeaway>Trust is not a feeling. It is a test suite, a trace, and a release gate.</Takeaway></DocsLayout>